# Workflow & Collaboration Rules

## Branching

- `main` — stable. One merge per completed phase. Never commit directly.
- `dev` — integration. All feature branches merge here via PR.
- `feature/phase-X-description` — one branch per issue.

## Commit Convention

Use Conventional Commits. Format:

```
<type>(<scope>): <short imperative description>
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `test`, `docs`, `refactor`, `chore`
Scopes: `server`, `android`, `bundle`, `routing`, `security`, `ci`

Examples:
- `feat(server): add bundle chunker for responses over 100KB`
- `fix(android): prevent Room migration crash on cold start`
- `test(server): add signature verification round-trip tests`

Rules:
- One logical change per commit.
- Never commit "misc", "WIP", or "various fixes".
- Commit message body is optional but encouraged for non-obvious changes.

## Issue Workflow

Every coding task corresponds to a GitHub issue. When the human gives you an issue:

1. Read the issue title and description carefully.
2. Identify which files are affected before writing code.
3. Implement the minimal change that satisfies the acceptance criteria.
4. After implementation, suggest what to test manually and what to unit test.

## AI Session Protocol

- The human will tell you the current issue number and phase at the start of a session.
- Stay focused on that one issue. Do not fix unrelated things you notice unless asked.
- If you discover something broken unrelated to the current issue, mention it but do not fix it.
- At the end of your work, summarize what you changed and what the human should review.

## Testing

- Server tests: `pytest server/tests/` — always suggest running after server changes.
- Android tests: manual on-device testing for Nearby/BLE features (no emulator support).
- When writing tests, follow existing test file patterns. Do not introduce a new test framework.
